@node Features "ClipWizard V1.1 - Features"

- ClipWizard is a commodity

- Easy to use install-script

- Amigaguide documentation

- A flexible @{"matchfile" LINK MatchFile} format

- Case-sensitivity/Case-insensitivity

- Can include the Clipboard contents in the command line

- Powerful @{"ARexx" LINK ARexxCommands} port
@endnode
@node Installation "ClipWizard V1.1 - Installation"
Please read the @{"Disclaimer" LINK Disclaimer} before installing.

Installation is quite simple. Just double-click on the "Install-ClipWizard"
icon, and answer a couple of questions.

After this you should drag the ClipWizard icon to SYS:WBStartup, so it will
be started on every boot.

You will also have to edit your @{"Matchfile" LINK Matchfile} and scripts to suit your needs.

If you cannot use the install-script for some reason, you can also
install ClipWizard by hand, using the following procedure:

1. Copy ClipWizard and it's icon to where-ever you want to install
   the program.

2. Copy ClipWizard.guide to where-ever you want to keep the documents

3. Copy Matchfile to where-ever you want to keep it. ENV:Matchfile
   is preferred (then you must of course also copy it to ENVARC:).

4. If you copied the Matchfile to something else than ENV:, 
   change the ClipWizards tooltype "MATCHFILE", so it can find
   your matchfile.

You are done.
@endnode
@node Matchfile "ClipWizard V1.1 - Matchfile"
Each entry in the matchfile takes three lines, first one for the string
to check for matches, second line is the command to execute, and third
line indicates if the match string of this entry should be considered
case-sensitive or not.

Matchfile has the following format:

1. line: String to check the matches for.
2. line: Command to be executed if the clipboard contents matches this 
         entry.
3. line: Options. Currently only "casesensitive" available

BTW: The options line is not case-sensitive.

The match string uses the normal AmigaDOS wildcards, e.g. "#?" or
"~(#?hello?world)"

Here is a full list of them, from the dos.library RKMs:

       ?       Matches a single character.
       #       Matches the following expression 0 or more times.
       (ab|cd) Matches any one of the items seperated by '|'.
       ~       Negates the following expression.  It matches all strings
               that do not match the expression (aka ~(foo) matches all
               strings that are not exactly "foo").
       [abc]   Character class: matches any of the characters in the class.
       [~bc]   Character class: matches any of the characters not in the
               class.
       a-z     Character range (only within character classes). 
       %       Matches 0 characters always (useful in "(foo|bar|%)").
       *       Synonym for "#?", not available by default in 2.0.  Available
               as an option that can be turned on.

"Expression" in the above table means either a single character
(ex: "#?"), or an alternation (ex: "#(ab|cd|ef)"), or a character
class (ex: "#[a-zA-Z]").

You should take a look at the @{"example matchfile" LINK "matchfile/main"} for a couple of examples.

You can use "%s" in the command line, so it will be substituted with
the clipboard contents. If there is a linefeed in the clipboard, it
will be clipped, and the rest of the clipboard will be executed as
a second command, just like trying to use a linefeed as a argument
in a normal shell.

@endnode
@node ExampleScripts "ClipWizard V1.1 - Example Scripts"
WWW-Page:

Adds the URL snapped to a selected URL-file with a description.

Edit the WWW-page to point to your URL-file. Requires @{"rexxreqtools" LINK ReqTools}.

PGP:

Runs PGP on the clipboard contents. It allows you to add new keys, verify
mails signatures etc. by simply snapping them.

Requires PGP. Edit the script so it can find PGP and PGP-startup
@endnode
@node ARexxCommands "ClipWizard V1.1 - ARexx commands"
ClipWizard gives you a quite powerful ARexx port in address "ClipWizard",
so you can use ARexx to command it. Here is a list of the commands
supported:

GetClipContents       Get the clipboard contents. The contents will be
		      copied to "result". Remember to specify "options
		      results".

CheckForMatches       Causes ClipWizard to immediately scan the matchfile
                      for possible matches.

QuitClipWizard        Quits ClipWizard

DisableClipWizard     Disables ClipWizard

EnableClipWizard      Enables ClipWizard

See @{"example scripts" LINK ExampleScripts} for examples of using ARexx commands.
@endnode
@node Updates "ClipWizard V1.1 - Updates"
You can always find the latest release from the Aminet. If you don't have
access to aminet, you can always order the latest version directly from me,
either by e-mail, or by sending me a letter with a disk included. See
@{"Author" LINK Author} for my address. The latest version will probably be
also available from the local BBS systems.

You can probably order the latest version of RexxReqTools directly from
the author, or find it in the Aminet. I got it from the
@{"ReqTools" LINK ReqTools} package, where it was included.
@endnode
@node FuturePlans "ClipWizard V1.1 - Future plans"
- A config program to make the configuring of the matchfile easier
- Improve the installation-script so you won't need to edit the scripts
- Support for other units than 0
- MagicWB icons (could someone please draw these for me? I'm not talented.
  If you're interested, please contact me)
- Ability to comment the matchfile
- Better ARexx support
- Better error handling. Currently it just quits/does nothing if something
  goes wrong

If you have any ideas, please send me a message. See @{"Author" LINK Author} for my
address.
@endnode
@node History "ClipWizard V1.1 - History"
--- 1.0 --- The first release. I after all only spread it to a couple
            of friends to test. I hope you never had this version :)
--- 1.1 --- Now uses AmigaDOS compatible wildcards. Changed the matchfile
            format a bit.

@endnode
